<p>The thermal stability of the oxohydroxoferrates was characterized by thermogravimetry (TG) and differential thermal analysis (DTA) up to 1000 °C for 
 <italic>
  <bold>K</bold>
 </italic>, to 600 °C for 
 <italic>
  <bold>Rb</bold>
 </italic> and 
 <italic>
  <bold>Cs</bold>
 </italic>, at a heating rate of 5 K min
 <sup>−1</sup> under inert conditions in an argon flow. The hydroxoferrates decompose to their anhydrides in the following manner:
 <disp-formula id="open201900287-disp-0001">
  <label>(1)</label>
  <math id="nlm-math-3">
   <mstyle displaystyle="true">
    <mrow>
     <mi>A</mi>
     <msub>
      <mrow/>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo>[</mo>
      <mi>Fe</mi>
      <msub>
       <mrow/>
       <mn>2</mn>
      </msub>
      <mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi>
      <msub>
       <mrow/>
       <mn>3</mn>
      </msub>
      <mrow>
       <mo>(</mo>
       <mi>OH</mi>
       <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <msub>
       <mrow/>
       <mn>2</mn>
      </msub>
      <mo>]</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>→</mo>
     <mn>2</mn>
     <mspace width="4pt"/>
     <mi>A</mi>
     <mi>FeO</mi>
     <msub>
      <mrow/>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi>
     <msub>
      <mrow/>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msub>
     <mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mstyle>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
